@Override
    protected Object decode(
            ChannelHandlerContext ctx, Channel channel, ByteBuf buf) throws Exception {
        // Check if there is enough data in the buffer to read the message length.
        if (buf.readableBytes() < 4) {
            return null; // Wait for more data
        }

        // Mark the readerIndex before reading the length. This allows us to reset the readerIndex if the message is incomplete.
        buf.markReaderIndex();

        // Read the message length (assuming it's a 4-byte integer).
        int length = buf.readInt();

        // Check if there is enough data in the buffer to read the entire message.
        if (buf.readableBytes() < length) {
            // Reset the readerIndex to the marked position.
            buf.resetReaderIndex();
            return null; // Wait for more data
        }

        // Read the message content.
        byte[] data = new byte[length];
        buf.readBytes(data);

        // Return the decoded message.  You'll likely want to replace this with your actual message type.
        return new String(data, "UTF-8"); 
    }
```

This implementation assumes messages are prefixed with a 4-byte integer representing their length.  It checks for sufficient data before attempting to read the length and message content. If not enough data is available, it returns `null` to indicate that more data is needed.  The message is then read and decoded assuming it's UTF-8 encoded.  You should replace `"UTF-8"` with the appropriate encoding if your messages use a different one and `new String(data, "UTF-8")` with the proper object instantiation for your message type.  For example, if you're using Protobuf, you would deserialize the `data` byte array into your Protobuf message object.

