@Override
    protected Object decode(
            Channel channel, SocketAddress remoteAddress, Object msg) throws Exception {
        // Check if the message is a ByteBuf
        if (!(msg instanceof ByteBuf)) {
            return msg; // Pass through non-ByteBuf messages
        }

        ByteBuf buf = (ByteBuf) msg;
        try {
            // Assuming a simple example where messages are prefixed with their length
            int length = buf.readInt();
            if (buf.readableBytes() < length) {
                // Insufficient data, return null to wait for more data
                buf.resetReaderIndex();
                return null;
            }
            byte[] data = new byte[length];
            buf.readBytes(data);
            //Further processing of data can be done here.  Example below converts to String.
            String decodedMessage = new String(data, "UTF-8"); // Or any other appropriate encoding
            return decodedMessage;


        } finally {
            // Ensure the buffer is released to avoid memory leaks
            buf.release();
        }
    }
```

This implementation assumes a simple message format where each message is prefixed with its length as an integer.  It checks if enough bytes are available. If not, it returns `null` to signal the decoder to wait for more data.  Otherwise, it reads the specified number of bytes, converts them to a String (using UTF-8 encoding – adjust as needed), and returns the decoded String.  Crucially, it releases the `ByteBuf` in a `finally` block to prevent memory leaks.  Remember to replace the string encoding and data processing with your specific needs.  If your message format is different, you'll need to adjust the decoding logic accordingly.  For example, you might use a delimiter instead of a length prefix or handle more complex structured data.

