import io.netty.buffer.ByteBuf;
import io.netty.channel.Channel;
import io.netty.channel.socket.SocketAddress;

import java.net.InetSocketAddress;

class Position {
    public final int x;
    public final int y;

    public Position(int x, int y) {
        this.x = x;
        this.y = y;
    }
}


private Position decodePosition(
        Channel channel, SocketAddress remoteAddress, ByteBuf buf, int index) {
    // Check if enough bytes are available
    if (buf.readableBytes() < index + 4) {
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("Not enough bytes to decode position");
    }

    // Read x and y coordinates from the buffer.  Assumes they are 2 bytes (short) each.
    int x = buf.getShort(index);
    int y = buf.getShort(index + 2);

    return new Position(x,y);
}
```

This function assumes that the position is encoded as two short integers (2 bytes each) representing the x and y coordinates, sequentially in the buffer.  It first checks if enough bytes are available to avoid `IndexOutOfBoundsException`.  Then it reads the values and returns a `Position` object.  Remember to replace the placeholder `Position` class with your actual implementation if it differs. If your encoding is different (e.g., using integers, floats, or a different byte order), you will need to adjust the `getShort()` calls and potentially the byte order using `buf.order(ByteOrder.BIG_ENDIAN)` or `buf.order(ByteOrder.LITTLE_ENDIAN)`.  The `Channel`, `SocketAddress`, and `index` parameters are not used in this specific implementation, but they might be useful in more complex scenarios (e.g., error handling or logging).

