private void printRow(final Help.TextTable table, final SearchResponse.Response.Doc doc) {
    if (doc == null) {
        return; // Handle null documents gracefully
    }

    List<String> row = new ArrayList<>();

    // Assuming SearchResponse.Response.Doc has fields like title, url, snippet etc.  Adjust field names as needed.
    row.add(doc.getTitle());
    row.add(doc.getUrl());
    row.add(doc.getSnippet());


    //Handle potential null values in doc fields.
    row.replaceAll(s -> s == null ? "" : s);


    table.addRow(row);
}
```

This improved version handles the case where `doc` might be null, preventing a `NullPointerException`.  It also adds error handling for null values within the `doc` object itself, replacing them with empty strings to avoid further exceptions. Remember to replace `"title"`, `"url"`, and `"snippet"` with the actual field names from your `SearchResponse.Response.Doc` class.  If your `Doc` class has more fields you want to display, add them to the `row` list accordingly.  The `replaceAll` method ensures that null values within the doc fields don't cause issues when adding the row to the table.

