import java.net.SocketAddress;
import java.text.ParseException;
import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

import io.netty.channel.Channel;

private Object decodeCan(Channel channel, SocketAddress remoteAddress, String sentence) throws ParseException {
    // Split the sentence into parts based on the CAN frame delimiter (e.g., ',')
    String[] parts = sentence.split(",");

    // Check if the sentence has enough parts for a valid CAN frame
    if (parts.length < 3) {
        throw new ParseException("Invalid CAN frame format: Not enough parts", 0);
    }

    // Extract CAN ID, data length, and data
    try {
        long canId = Long.parseLong(parts[0], 16); // Assuming hex ID
        int dataLength = Integer.parseInt(parts[1]);
        byte[] data = new byte[dataLength];
        if (parts.length < 3 + dataLength) {
            throw new ParseException("Invalid CAN frame format: Data length mismatch", 0);
        }
        for (int i = 0; i < dataLength; i++) {
            data[i] = (byte) Integer.parseInt(parts[i + 2], 16); // Assuming hex data
        }

        //Create a map to hold the CAN frame data.  This allows for flexible return types.
        Map<String, Object> canFrame = new HashMap<>();
        canFrame.put("canId", canId);
        canFrame.put("dataLength", dataLength);
        canFrame.put("data", data);
        canFrame.put("remoteAddress", remoteAddress);
        canFrame.put("channel", channel);


        return canFrame;


    } catch (NumberFormatException e) {
        throw new ParseException("Invalid CAN frame format: Number format exception", 0);
    } catch (ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException e){
        throw new ParseException("Invalid CAN frame format: Array index out of bounds", 0);
    }
}
```

This improved version handles potential exceptions more robustly:

* **`NumberFormatException`:** Catches errors if the CAN ID or data bytes aren't valid hexadecimal numbers.
* **`ParseException`:** Provides more informative error messages indicating the nature of the parsing problem.
* **`ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException`:** Handles cases where the input string doesn't have enough elements.
* **Data Length Check:** Explicitly checks if the number of data parts matches the declared data length.
* **Return Type:** Returns a `Map` instead of a custom object, offering flexibility in how the decoded data is used.  This makes the function more reusable.  You can easily adjust the map keys to match your specific needs.


Remember to replace the delimiter (`,`) if your CAN frame uses a different separator.  Also, adjust the parsing of the CAN ID and data (currently assuming hexadecimal representation) to match your specific CAN frame format.  If you are using a specific CAN library, you may want to leverage its existing parsing capabilities for better error handling and efficiency.

