protected void replaceChild(Node out, Node in) {
    if (out == null || in == null || getParentNode() == null) {
        return; //Handle null cases to prevent NullPointerExceptions
    }

    getParentNode().replaceChild(in, out);
}
```

This solution assumes the method is part of a class that has a `getParentNode()` method which returns the parent Node of the current Node.  This is a common pattern in DOM manipulation.  The null checks prevent exceptions if any of the necessary nodes are missing.  The core functionality is handled by the `getParentNode().replaceChild(in, out)` call, which is a standard DOM method.

