```java
import io.netty.buffer.ByteBuf;

private void readBinaryCustomData(Position position, ByteBuf buf, String form) {
    if (buf == null) {
        return; // Handle null buffer gracefully
    }

    switch (form) {
        case "int":
            position.setInt(buf.readInt());
            break;
        case "long":
            position.setLong(buf.readLong());
            break;
        case "float":
            position.setFloat(buf.readFloat());
            break;
        case "double":
            position.setDouble(buf.readDouble());
            break;
        case "short":
            position.setShort(buf.readShort());
            break;
        case "byte":
            position.setByte(buf.readByte());
            break;
        case "boolean":
            position.setBoolean(buf.readBoolean());
            break;
        case "char":
            position.setChar(buf.readChar());
            break;
        case "string":
            int stringLength = buf.readInt(); // Assuming string length is prefixed
            if (stringLength > 0) {
                byte[] stringBytes = new byte[stringLength];
                buf.readBytes(stringBytes);
                position.setString(new String(stringBytes));
            } else {
                position.setString(""); // Handle empty strings
            }
            break;
        default:
            // Handle unsupported forms or throw an exception
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Unsupported data form: " + form);
    }
}
```

This solution assumes the `Position` class has appropriate setter methods (`setInt`, `setLong`, etc.) for each data type.  It also assumes that strings are prefixed with their length (as an integer) in the `ByteBuf`.  Error handling is included for a null `ByteBuf` and unsupported data forms.  You'll need to adapt the string handling and error handling to your specific needs and the definition of your `Position` class.  For more robust error handling, consider using exceptions with more specific information.

