```java
/** Binary operations on arbitrary objects.
     * @param lhs left hand side value
     * @param rhs right hand side value
     * @param kind operator type
     * @return operator applied value
     * @throws UtilEvalError evaluation error */
    @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
    public static Object arbitraryObjectsBinaryOperation(
        Object lhs, Object rhs, int kind)
        throws UtilEvalError {
        if (lhs == null || rhs == null) {
            throw new UtilEvalError("Null operand");
        }

        switch (kind) {
            case Operator.ADD:
                if (lhs instanceof Number && rhs instanceof Number) {
                    return ((Number) lhs).doubleValue() + ((Number) rhs).doubleValue();
                } else if (lhs instanceof String || rhs instanceof String) {
                    return lhs.toString() + rhs.toString();
                } else {
                    throw new UtilEvalError("Unsupported operand types for +");
                }
            case Operator.SUBTRACT:
                if (lhs instanceof Number && rhs instanceof Number) {
                    return ((Number) lhs).doubleValue() - ((Number) rhs).doubleValue();
                } else {
                    throw new UtilEvalError("Unsupported operand types for -");
                }
            case Operator.MULTIPLY:
                if (lhs instanceof Number && rhs instanceof Number) {
                    return ((Number) lhs).doubleValue() * ((Number) rhs).doubleValue();
                } else {
                    throw new UtilEvalError("Unsupported operand types for *");
                }
            case Operator.DIVIDE:
                if (lhs instanceof Number && rhs instanceof Number) {
                    double rhsVal = ((Number) rhs).doubleValue();
                    if (rhsVal == 0) {
                        throw new UtilEvalError("Division by zero");
                    }
                    return ((Number) lhs).doubleValue() / rhsVal;
                } else {
                    throw new UtilEvalError("Unsupported operand types for /");
                }
            case Operator.EQUAL:
                return lhs.equals(rhs);
            case Operator.NOT_EQUAL:
                return !lhs.equals(rhs);
            case Operator.LESS_THAN:
                if (lhs instanceof Comparable && rhs instanceof Comparable) {
                    return ((Comparable) lhs).compareTo(rhs) < 0;
                } else {
                    throw new UtilEvalError("Unsupported operand types for <");
                }
            case Operator.GREATER_THAN:
                if (lhs instanceof Comparable && rhs instanceof Comparable) {
                    return ((Comparable) lhs).compareTo(rhs) > 0;
                } else {
                    throw new UtilEvalError("Unsupported operand types for >");
                }
            case Operator.LESS_THAN_OR_EQUAL:
                if (lhs instanceof Comparable && rhs instanceof Comparable) {
                    return ((Comparable) lhs).compareTo(rhs) <= 0;
                } else {
                    throw new UtilEvalError("Unsupported operand types for <=");
                }
            case Operator.GREATER_THAN_OR_EQUAL:
                if (lhs instanceof Comparable && rhs instanceof Comparable) {
                    return ((Comparable) lhs).compareTo(rhs) >= 0;
                } else {
                    throw new UtilEvalError("Unsupported operand types for >=");
                }
            default:
                throw new UtilEvalError("Unknown operator");
        }
    }
```

This solution handles addition for both numbers and strings, and other arithmetic operations for numbers only.  It also includes comparisons for `Comparable` objects.  Error handling is included for null operands, division by zero, and unsupported operand types for each operator.  Remember that you'll need a `UtilEvalError` class and an `Operator` class (containing integer constants for operator types) defined elsewhere in your project for this code to compile and run correctly.  For example:

```java
class UtilEvalError extends Exception {
    public UtilEvalError(String message) {
        super(message);
    }
}

class Operator {
    public static final int ADD = 1;
    public static final int SUBTRACT = 2;
    public static final int MULTIPLY = 3;
    public static final int DIVIDE = 4;
    public static final int EQUAL = 5;
    public static final int NOT_EQUAL = 6;
    public static final int LESS_THAN = 7;
    public static final int GREATER_THAN = 8;
    public static final int LESS_THAN_OR_EQUAL = 9;
    public static final int GREATER_THAN_OR_EQUAL = 10;
}
```
Remember to adapt these classes to your specific needs.

