import org.jsoup.nodes.Document;
import java.io.IOException;

class MyUtils {
    void outerHtmlHead(Appendable accum, int depth, Document.OutputSettings out) throws IOException {
        accum.append("<head>\n");
        for (org.jsoup.nodes.Element child : out.getDocument().head().childNodes()) {
            child.outerHtml(accum, depth + 1, out);
        }
        accum.append("</head>\n");

    }
}
```

This solution assumes the existence of a `Document` object within the `out` `OutputSettings` object.  It iterates through each child node of the `<head>` element and calls `outerHtml` recursively to append the HTML representation of each child.  The `\n` characters add newlines for readability.  Error handling is minimal because the `outerHtml` method itself likely handles IOExceptions internally.  If you need more robust error handling, you might wrap the `child.outerHtml` call in a `try-catch` block.  Note that this requires the JSoup library.  You'll need to add it as a dependency to your project.

